{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619477"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:32:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:32:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16559"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16559"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0.16,0.04,0.08,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9250"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80679"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9250"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16559"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65975"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1708"},{"type":"tags","id":"2457"},{"type":"tags","id":"3935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5917"},{"type":"tags","id":"7162"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21913"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21917"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80679"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man is reviewed three days after an out-of-hospital cardiac arrest. The medical team notes fluctuating weakness of both shoulders and hips. His distal limb strength is preserved. Brain imaging reveals bilateral watershed infarcts.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the arterial territories involved in this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior cerebral artery-middle cerebral artery","Middle cerebral artery-posterior cerebral artery","Anterior cerebral artery-posterior cerebral artery","Posterior cerebral artery-vertebral artery","Middle cerebral artery-vertebral artery"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation describes person-in-barrel syndrome, which results from \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior cerebral artery-middle cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E watershed infarcts. These bilateral infarcts affect the superior portions of the motor homunculus that control proximal limb function, resulting in weakness of shoulders and hips while preserving distal limb strength.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMiddle cerebral artery-posterior cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E watershed infarcts typically affect the occipito-parietal regions causing visual processing disorders\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior cerebral artery-posterior cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E watershed areas do not exist anatomically as these arteries are not adjacent\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior cerebral artery-vertebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E watershed infarcts would affect the posterior circulation territory\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMiddle cerebral artery-vertebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E watershed areas do not exist anatomically\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWatershed infarcts occur in border zones between major cerebral arterial territories and typically result from severe hypoperfusion, as seen following cardiac arrest.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Person-in-barrel syndrome results from bilateral anterior cerebral artery-middle cerebral artery watershed infarcts causing proximal arm weakness with preserved leg function.","Watershed infarcts occur in areas between major arterial territories and are typically caused by severe hypoperfusion.","Anterior cerebral artery-middle cerebral artery watershed areas supply the superior portions of the motor homunculus controlling proximal limb function."],"references":["Nogles TE, Galuska MA. Middle Cerebral Artery Stroke. 2023 Apr 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32310592.","Rouanet C, Reges D, Rocha E, Gagliardi V, Uehara MK, Miranda MA, Silva GS. \u0022Man in the Barrel\u0022 Syndrome with Anterior Spinal Artery Infarct due to Vertebral Artery Dissection. J Stroke Cerebrovasc Dis. 2017 Mar;26(3):e41-e42. doi: 10.1016/j.jstrokecerebrovasdis.2016.12.016. Epub 2017 Jan 5. PMID: 28065615.","Shields LBE, Iyer VG, Zhang YP, Shields CB. Person-in-the-barrel syndrome following cervical spine surgery: illustrative case. J Neurosurg Case Lessons. 2021 Feb 22;1(8):CASE20165. doi: 10.3171/CASE20165. PMID: 35855313; PMCID: PMC9241343."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65975"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16559"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65975"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T09:20:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T09:20:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9250"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80679"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09: